          <td>Good</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Subsoil</td>
          <td>20-40</td>
          <td>6.5</td>
          <td>0.5</td>
          <td>1.8</td>
          <td>18</td>
          <td>9</td>
          <td>110</td>
          <td>Loamy sand</td>
          <td>Moderate</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Substratum</td>
          <td>40-60</td>
          <td>6.8</td>
          <td>0.3</td>
          <td>1.5</td>
          <td>15</td>
          <td>7</td>
          <td>100</td>
          <td>Sandy clay</td>
          <td>Poor</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p class="soil_report">Interpretation :</p>
    <ul>
      <li>pH (H2O): The pH levels across all depths fall within the optimal range (6.0-7.0) for most crops, ensuring
        nutrient availability and microbial activity.</li>
      <li>Electrical Conductivity (EC): The EC values indicate low salinity levels, which are favorablElectrical
        Conductivity (EC): The EC values indicate low salinity levels, which are favorable for plant growth. However,
        monitoring is recommended to prevent salinity buildup over time.</li>
      <li>Organic Matter (%): Organic matter content is moderate, contributing to soil fertility, water retention, and
        microbial activity. Incorporating organic amendments can further enhance soil health.</li>
      <li>Total Nitrogen (N): Adequate nitrogen levels support plant growth and protein synthesis. Nitrogen management
        strategies should consider crop requirements and potential leaching losses.</li>
      <li>Phosphorus (P): Phosphorus levels are sufficient for initial plant growth but may require supplementation for
        optimal yields, especially in phosphorus-fixing soils.</li>
      <li>Potassium (K): Potassium levels are adequate for most crops, supporting functions such as enzyme activation,
        water regulation, and disease resistance.</li>
      <li>Texture: Soil texture influences water infiltration, root penetration, and nutrient availability. Adjusting
        management practices based on texture can optimize crop performance.</li>
      <li>Drainage: Soil drainage affects root development, oxygen availability, and nutrient uptake. Improving drainage
        in poorly drained areas can mitigate waterlogging and enhance crop resilience.</li>
    </ul>
